    "description": "The Mark of St. Crispin and other short stories is the complete collection of nine short stories written by Virginia Moriconi between 1953 and 1982. Motley Press invites you to plunge into the profoundly unsettling world she created and witness her masterful incorporation of bizarre and disturbing situations that lurk beneath the surface of everyday life. These short stories masterfully blend the everyday with the surreal. We meet a shoe salesman lost in mundane daydreams, a son watching his mother harden into a statue, a wife unearthing her husband’s secrets, and a doctor grappling with hippies and a dead baby. Relationships disintegrate under collapsing bridges, the veneer of rural peace shatters into neighbourly war and a sickly quail takes over an entire family. For this new edition in 2025, we included the  rediscovered story “The Innocence of Rachel Crewe”. In this haunting tale, a bookseller’s marriage to a beautiful and intelligent young woman holds terrible secrets that threaten to shatter their present. Accompanying these stories are the editor’s notes to offer valuable historical context and commentary on the social and cultural landscapes that shaped Moriconi’s writing.",
